{
  "title": "Philosophische Bemerkungen zu mehrwertigen Systemen",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "d9c86c28f9a581f4",
      "text": "Łukasiewicz 1930\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "0744c6aabfb41cde",
      "text": "When he recognized the incompatibility of the traditional theorems about modal propositions in 1920, he was busy building up the system of the ordinary \"two-valued\" propositional calculus by means of the matrix method. He convinced himself at that time that all theses of the ordinary [[propositional calculus]] can be proved, if one presupposes that the propositional variables contained in them may take only two values, \"0\" or \"the false\" and \"1\" or \"the true\".\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "eccd7ee65254513b",
      "text": "This assumption corresponds to the principle that every statement is either true or false. We would like to call this principle briefly the \"two-valuedness theorem\" („Zweiwertigkeitssatz“). Although it is sometimes called the theorem of the excluded third (Satz vom ausgeschlossenen Dritten), we think it is better to keep this latter name for the well-known principle of classical logic, according to which two contradictory statements cannot be false at the same time.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "d01eb18702dfe9ab",
      "text": "The two-valued proposition is the deepest, but already in antiquity fiercely disputed foundation of our entire logic. Known by Aristoteles, but disputed for statements referring to future random events, decisively denied by the Epicureans, the two-valued proposition appears in its full sharpness only with Chrysippos and the Stoics, namely as a principle of their dialectic representing the ancient propositional calculus.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "9c5075512d5baf54",
      "text": "The dispute about the two-valued proposition has a metaphysical background: the supporters of this proposition are decided [[determinists]], while the opponents of the proposition tend to the indeterministic worldview. This brings us back to the circle of the concepts of possibility and necessity.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "4bdc9929149e8bcf",
      "text": "The deepest principle of logic does not seem to be quite evident after all. Based on time-honored examples reaching up to Aristoteles, Łukasiewicz tried to overcome the two-valued theorem by empathizing with the following trains of thought:\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "9097137176f809c0",
      "text": "> I can assume without contradiction that my presence in Warsaw at a certain moment of time next year, e.g. at noon on December 21, is nowadays neither decided in a positive nor in a negative sense. It is therefore possible, but not necessary, that I will be present in Warsaw at the given time. Under this condition, the statement: \"I will be present in Warsaw at noon on December 21 of next year\" can be neither true nor false today. For if it were true today, my future presence in Warsaw would have to be necessary, which contradicts the premise; and if it were false today, my future presence in Warsaw would have to be impossible, which also contradicts the premise. Therefore, the proposition under consideration is nowadays neither true nor false and must have a third value, different from \"0\" or the false and from „1\" or the true. We can designate this value as \"½\"; it is just \"the possible\", which comes as a third value beside \"the false\" and \"the true\".\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ccc3eda5efd2078c",
      "text": "The three-valued system of the propositional calculus owes its origin to this train of thought. Now the matrix had to be given, on the basis of which the new system of logic could be defined.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "6525c2f6795f7174",
      "text": "> It was immediately clear to me that if the statement concerning my future presence in Warsaw has the value ½, then its negation must also have the same value ½.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "97c732cd40def6f5",
      "text": "Next: [[Definition of the Concept of Possibility]]"
    }
