        "text": "The deepest principle of logic does not seem to be quite evident after all. Based on time-honored examples reaching up to Aristoteles, Łukasiewicz tried to overcome the two-valued theorem by empathizing with the following trains of thought:\n> I can assume without contradiction that my presence in Warsaw at a certain moment of time next year, e.g. at noon on December 21, is nowadays neither decided in a positive nor in a negative sense. It is therefore possible, but not necessary, that I will be present in Warsaw at the given time. Under this condition, the statement: \"I will be present in Warsaw at noon on December 21 of next year\" can be neither true nor false today. For if it were true today, my future presence in Warsaw would have to be necessary, which contradicts the premise; and if it were false today, my future presence in Warsaw would have to be impossible, which also contradicts the premise. Therefore, the proposition under consideration is nowadays neither true nor false and must have a third value, different from \"0\" or the false and from „1\" or the true. We can designate this value as \"½\"; it is just \"the possible\", which comes as a third value beside \"the false\" and \"the true\"."
